<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94 / THE FIRST ROUND; TODAY'S GAME AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WILLIAM D. MONTALBANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 GROUP D at Foxboro Stadium, Foxboro, Ma. 
</P>
<P>
 Argentina vs. Greece 
</P>
<P>
 * TIME: 9:30 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 * TV: ESPN, Univision, KSCI (Greek) 
</P>
<P>
 * KEY MATCHUPS: Once again, the world will be watching Diego Maradona in this 
best-of-times opener for the Argentines, and worst-of-times debut for the 
rookie Greeks.Playing in their first Cup after nearly seven decades of trying, 
it will take a miracle for Greece to survive the opening round in a group that 
also includes Nigeria and Bulgaria. The Argentines, by contrast, should cruise 
through, although they appear to have lost a step since their 1990 second-place 
finish. Maradona, 33, says he's fit. So, too, are Argentine strikers who play 
their club soccer in Italy: Roma's Abel Balbo and Claudio Caniggia, and 
Fiorentina's Gabriel Batistuta. That trio should prove too much for a no-name 
Greek defense playing around 35-year-old keeper Antonis Minou. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTLOOK: The Argentines had qualifying problems and their usual spate of 
feuds and rancor on their way to the Cup. Still, look for Maradona and fellow 
midfielders Leonardo Rodrigues and Diego Simeone to gain quick control of a 
game that will be mostly played at Argentina's pace -- and on Greece's end of 
the field. Argentine keeper Sergio Goycochea, hero of Italia '90, is back, 
symbol of an Argentine defense that is aging and suspect to quick, vigorous 
attack. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTCOME: If you've a mind to celebrate ethnically, hold the feta . Order 
steak. Argentina by at least two goals, but if the Greeks lose their poise it 
could be a rout. WILLIAM D. MONTALBANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA062194-0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 053245 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
June 21, 1994, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 5; Column 5; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
228 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94 / THE FIRST ROUND; TODAY'S GAME AT A GLANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELLIOTT ALMOND 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 GROUP D at the Cotton Bowl, Dallas 
</P>
<P>
 Bulgaria vs. Nigeria 
</P>
<P>
 * TIME: 4:35 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 * TV: ESPN2, Univision, (ESPN tape, 10:25) 
</P>
<P>
 * KEY MATCHUPS: Dimitar Penev, Bulgaria's coach, would not say Monday whether 
he will use two or three forwards.But most likely the Bulgarians will rely on 
Hristo Stoichkov's deadly left foot on counterattacks. Although Stoichkov, who 
plays for BC Barcelona, has a slight hamstring pull, he should be ready. 
</P>
<P>
 The Bulgarians will have to be cautious against the African champions. If 
teen-age midfielders Sunday Oliseh and Austin Okocha can control their 
counterparts, Nigeria has the firepower to explode. Striker Rashidi Yekini is 
poised to emerge as one of the stars of the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTLOOK: Bulgaria has yet to win a World Cup match in six appearances, three 
with Penev as a central forward. After its dramatic qualifying victory over 
France last November in Paris, Bulgarians are hoping for a new era of Balkan 
soccer. 
</P>
<P>
 Nigeria, on the other hand, will make its World Cup debut with great 
expectations after Cameroon's quarterfinal finish in 1990. So, each team is 
under pressure to perform, but particularly the favored Africans. 
</P>
<P>
 * OUTCOME: The Bulgarians know the reputation of the Super Eagles, and hope 
they can sneak up on them with one of Europe's most potent attacks. We think 
they will. Bulgaria, 2-1. ELLIOTT ALMOND 
</P>
</TEXT>
