<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN SUPPORT OF DARE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 I am a Chapter I teacher at El Rancho Structured School. I attended the 
hearing on May 11 regarding funding for the DARE program in the Camarillo 
schools.Due to my observations at the meeting, I felt compelled to express my 
feelings regarding the DARE program. 
</P>
<P>
 Last year, I was working as a teacher in the Los Angeles Unified School 
District. I was able to observe firsthand the excellent program that the DARE 
officers present to the students, as well as the positive long-term effects on 
the children. During one of the sessions on how to deal with the knowledge that 
someone you know is using drugs, a fifth-grade female student of mine became 
noticeably upset. Because of her relationship with our DARE officer, she was 
able to confide that her 16-year-old brother was using drugs and she had known 
about it for some time. She had been suppressing her fears and anxieties for 
months, and this DARE presentation offered her the opportunity to deal with her 
feelings and the realities regarding the situation and her brother. 
</P>
<P>
 At the local meeting, it was stressed several times that the research shows 
there is no decrease in drug-related arrests where there is a DARE program in 
effect. I feel the statistics can't possibly show the many times the DARE 
program helps distressed young people either with their own problems regarding 
drugs or the problems someone close to them is having. Why do we have to wait 
until they become a statistic for the support of this superb program to become 
validated? Our children need this assistance before the fact, not after it. 
</P>
<P>
 SHARON MERESMAN 
</P>
<P>
 Camarillo 
</P>
</TEXT>
